UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 420
1 AN ACT relating to traffic control signal monitoring systems.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 SECTION 1. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 189 IS CREATED TO
4 READ AS FOLLOWS:
5 As used in Sections 1 to 4 of this Act:
6 (1) "Agency" means the law enforcement agency within a consolidated local
7 government organized and governed under KRS Chapter 67C primarily
8 responsible for traffic control at a particular intersection or that law enforcement
9 agency's designee;
10 (2) "Owner":
11 (a) Means the registered owner of a motor vehicle or a lessee of a motor vehicle
12 under a lease of six (6) months or more; and
13 (b) Does not include a motor vehicle rental or leasing company or holder of a
14 motor vehicle dealer plate issued under KRS 186.053;
15 (3) "Recorded images" means images recorded by a traffic control signal monitoring
16 system:
17 (a) On two (2) or more photographs, microphotographs, or electronic images,
18 or on videotape or any other medium; and
19 (b) Showing the rear of a motor vehicle, and on at least one (1) image or
20 portion of tape, clearly identifying the registration plate number of the
21 motor vehicle; and
22 (4) "Traffic control signal monitoring system" means a device with one (1) or more
23 vehicle sensors working in conjunction with a traffic control signal to produce
24 recorded images of a motor vehicle entering an intersection against a red signal
25 indication.
26 SECTION 2. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 189 IS CREATED TO
27 READ AS FOLLOWS:
Page 1 of 12
XXXX 9/23/2025 12:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 420
1 (1) Unless the operator of a motor vehicle received a citation from a police officer at
2 the time of the violation, the operator of a motor vehicle is subject to a civil
3 penalty of fifty dollars ($50) if the motor vehicle is recorded by a traffic control
4 signal monitoring system while being in violation of subsection (2) of Section 5 of
5 this Act.
6 (2) Forty-five dollars ($45) of the revenue generated from a civil penalty for traffic
7 control signal monitoring system violations shall be retained by the local
8 government, and five dollars ($5) shall be sent to the Administrative Office of the
9 Courts.
10 (3) To carry out the purposes of this section, the Administrative Office of the Courts,
11 in consultation with the Transportation Cabinet, shall prescribe a uniform civil
12 citation form, which shall include:
13 (a) The name and address of the registered owner of the motor vehicle;
14 (b) The name and address of the operator of the motor vehicle, if different from
15 the owner;
16 (c) The violation charged;
17 (d) The date and time of the violation;
18 (e) The location of the intersection;
19 (f) The amount of the civil penalty imposed and the date by which the civil
20 penalty should be paid;
21 (g) Information advising the person alleged to be liable under this section as to
22 the manner and time in which the citation may be contested in District
23 Court; and
24 (h) A warning that failure to pay the civil penalty imposed or to contest the
25 matter in a timely manner is an admission of liability and shall result in the
26 suspension of the registration of the motor vehicle.
27 (4) An agency shall mail to the owner of a motor vehicle liable under subsection (1)
Page 2 of 12
XXXX 9/23/2025 12:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 420
1 of this section, or other person identified as operating the motor vehicle:
2 (a) A uniform civil citation as described in subsection (3) of this section;
3 (b) A copy of the recorded images; and
4 (c) A signed, sworn statement by a technician employed by the agency that,
5 based on inspection of recorded images, the motor vehicle was being
6 operated in violation of subsection (2) of Section 5 of this Act. This
7 statement may be admissible in any proceeding alleging a violation under
8 this section.
9 (5) An agency may mail a warning notice instead of a citation to the owner of a
10 motor vehicle liable under subsection (1) of this section.
11 (6) Except as provided for in subsection (2) of Section 3 of this Act, a citation shall
12 be mailed no later than fourteen (14) days after the alleged violation.
13 (7) A person who receives a citation under this section may:
14 (a) Pay the civil penalty in accordance with the instructions on the citation
15 directly to the District Court; or
16 (b) Elect to stand trial for the alleged violation.
17 SECTION 3. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 189 IS CREATED TO
18 READ AS FOLLOWS:
19 (1) The court may consider in defense of a violation under Section 2 of this Act that:
20 (a) The operator of the motor vehicle passed through the intersection in
21 violation of subsection (2) of Section 5 of this Act in order to yield right-of-
22 way to an emergency vehicle, at the direction of a peace officer, or as part of
23 a funeral procession;
24 (b) The motor vehicle or the motor vehicle registration plates were stolen before
25 the violation occurred and were not under the control or possession of the
26 owner at the time of the violation;
27 (c) Section 2 of this Act is not enforceable because at the time and place of the
Page 3 of 12
XXXX 9/23/2025 12:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 420
1 violation, the traffic control signal was not in the proper position or
2 discernible enough to be seen by an ordinarily observant individual; and
3 (d) The person named in the citation was not operating the motor vehicle at the
4 time of the violation. A person named in a citation who uses this defense
5 shall identify who was operating the motor vehicle at the time of the
6 violation, including, at a minimum, the operator's name and address.
7 (2) If the District Court finds that the person named in the citation was not operating
8 the motor vehicle at the time of the violation, the clerk of the District Court shall
9 provide to the agency issuing the citation a copy of any evidence substantiating
10 who was operating the motor vehicle at the time of the violation. Upon receipt of
11 substantiating evidence from the District Court, the agency may issue a citation
12 under Section 2 of this Act to the person the evidence indicates was operating the
13 motor vehicle at the time of the violation. The agency shall issue the citation
14 within fourteen (14) days of receipt of the evidence from the District Court.
15 SECTION 4. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 189 IS CREATED TO
16 READ AS FOLLOWS:
17 (1) If a person refuses to pay the civil penalty imposed under Section 2 of this Act
18 and does not contest the violation, the Transportation Cabinet shall suspend the
19 registration of the motor vehicle, when notified by the District Court, until the
20 civil penalty is paid.
21 (2) A violation under Section 2 of this Act shall not result in points assessed against
22 the driving record of the operator of the motor vehicle in violation.
23 Section 5. KRS 189.231 is amended to read as follows:
24 (1) The secretary of transportation may install and maintain traffic control devices upon
25 state-maintained highways in such manner as is reasonably necessary to promote
26 the safety and convenience of the traveling public.
27 (2) The driver of any vehicle shall obey the instructions of any official traffic control
Page 4 of 12
XXXX 9/23/2025 12:07 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 420
1 device applicable thereto unless otherwise directed by a traffic or police officer,
2 subject to the exceptions granted the driver of an authorized emergency vehicle.
3 (3) The secretary of transportation may restrict or regulate traffic upon state-maintained
4 highways in such a manner as is reasonably necessary to promote the safety of the
5 traveling public.
6 (4) Law enforcement agencies within a consolidated local government organized and
7 governed under KRS Chapter 67C may use traffic control signal monitoring
8 systems as defined in Section 1 of this Act to enforce civil penalties for violation
9 of subsection (2) of this section.
10 Section 6. KRS 189.990 is amended to read as follows:
